<center><h2>A story worth telling...</h2></center>

<p>Around 2009, a small group of entrepreneurs, who mostly prefer to remain anonymous, became concerned with a couple of trends that seemed to fit together to create a dangerous imbalance.</p>

<p>On the one hand, privacy and information flow in Internet-based communications has been severely compromised, with corporate and government agencies being able to access and profit by personally identifiable information and no real corresponding transparency on the part of these agencies to balance the situation.</p>

<p>On the other hand, capital has been concentrating in such a small sector of society as to virtually cease to perform its principal function: provide a tool whereby we can all take care of each other and the planet.</p>

<p>We set out to build an alternative Internet-scale social communications platform to address both trends. Beginning from a sound mathematical theory that informs both a notion of distributed identity and the software architecture, we've built a distributed communications fabric designed to allow people to be in control of who sees their communications and who profits by them.</p>

<center><h3>How BitCoin changes the equation</h3></center>
<p><a href="https://docs.google.com/document/d/1aM5OIJWOyW89rHdUg6d9-YVbItdtxxiosP_fXZQaRdg/edit#heading=h.ndihpob06tu0">While i'm certainly very excited about the maths, and the way it simplifies the programming</a>, i'm equally excited about the possibility that this platform can help people find alternative ways of supporting each other directly. You see, we knew that the network was eventually going to have to become self-sustaining economically, and wanted to find a model that didn't interfere with the fundamentally distributed nature of the system. With the emergence of BitCoin (BTC) we feel we've found a solution.</p>

<p>Knowing that the corporate exchange of personal information (including personally identifiable information) is a >9B USD market, we feel it should be possible to turn the whole model on its head. Having already put a novel social media UI on the front end of our communications platform, allowing for people to search communications in their social network to which they have access, we realized we could just let people decide for themselves how much that information was worth to them, and using BTC, directly support people who provided them with information they found valuable.</p>

